243:
Let $S$ be a set.

For each $x \in S$, let there be given a set $\mathcal N_x$ of subsets of $S$ which satisfy the neighborhood space axioms:

{{begin-axiom}}
{{axiom|n = N1
       |lc= There exists at least one element in $\mathcal N_x$
       |q = \forall x \in S
       |m = \mathcal N_x \ne \varnothing
}}
{{axiom|n = N2
       |lc= Each element $x$ is in its own $\mathcal N_x$
       |q = \forall x \in S
       |m = \forall N \in \mathcal N_x: x \in N
}}
{{axiom|n = N3
       |lc= Each superset of $N \in \mathcal N_x$ is also in $\mathcal N_x$
       |q = \forall x \in S: \forall N \in \mathcal N_x
       |m = N' \supseteq N \implies N' \in \mathcal N_x
}}
{{axiom|n = N4
       |lc= Intersection of $2$ elements of $\mathcal N_x$ is also in $\mathcal N_x$
       |q = \forall x \in S: \forall M, N \in \mathcal N_x
       |m = M \cap N \in N_x
}}
{{axiom|n = N5
       |lc= Exists $N' \subseteq N \in \mathcal N_x$ which is $\mathcal N_y$ of each $y \in N'$
       |q = \forall x \in S: \forall N \in \mathcal N_x
       |m = \exists N' \in \mathcal N_x, N' \subseteq N: \forall y \in N': N' \in \mathcal N_y
}}
{{end-axiom}}

The sets $\mathcal N_x$ are the neighborhoods of $x$ in $S$.


Let $\mathcal N$ be the set of open sets of $S$:
:$\mathcal N = \left\{{U \subseteq S: U}\right.$ is a neighborhood of each of its elements $\left.{}\right\}$


The set $S$ together with $\mathcal N$ is called a '''neighborhood space''' and is denoted $\left({S, \mathcal N}\right)$.

