        | t = $S$ is closed under $\vee$, $\wedge$ and $\neg$
}}
{{axiom | n = BA_1 \ 1
        | lc=
        | t = Both $\vee$ and $\wedge$ are commutative
}}
{{axiom | n = BA_1 \ 2
        | lc=
        | t = Both $\vee$ and $\wedge$ distribute over the other
}}
{{axiom | n = BA_1 \ 3
        | lc=
        | t = Both $\vee$ and $\wedge$ have identities $\bot$ and $\top$ respectively
}}
{{axiom | n = BA_1 \ 4
        | lc=
        | t = $\forall a \in S: a \vee \neg a = \top, a \wedge \neg a = \bot$
}}
{{end-axiom}}


The operations $\vee$ and $\wedge$ are called '''join''' and '''meet''', respectively.

The identities $\bot$ and $\top$ are called '''bottom''' and '''top''', respectively.

The operation $\neg$ is called '''complementation'''.







Some sources define a Boolean algebra to be what on {{ProofWiki}} is called a Boolean lattice.


Some sources define a Boolean algebra to be a set with two elements (typically $\set {0, 1}$ together with the two operations '''addition''' $+$ and '''multiplication''' $\times$ defined as follows:

