4986:
Let $S$ be a set.

Let $\powerset S$ denote the power set of $S$.







A '''filter on $S$''' (or '''filter of $S$''') is a set $\mathcal F \subset \powerset S$ which satisfies the following conditions:

{{begin-axiom}}
{{axiom | n = 1
        | m = S \in \mathcal F
}}
{{axiom | n = 2
        | m = \O \notin \mathcal F
}}
{{axiom | n = 3
        | m = U, V \in \mathcal F \implies U \cap V \in \mathcal F
}}
{{axiom | n = 4
        | m = \forall U \in \mathcal F: U \subseteq V \subseteq S \implies V \in \mathcal F
}}
{{end-axiom}}







A '''filter on $S$''' (or '''filter of $S$''') is a set $\mathcal F \subset \powerset S$ which satisfies the following conditions:

{{begin-axiom}}
{{axiom | n = 1
        | m = S \in \mathcal F
}}
{{axiom | n = 2
        | m = \O \notin \mathcal F
}}
{{axiom | n = 3
        | m = \forall n \in \N: U_1, \ldots, U_n \in \mathcal F \implies \bigcap_{i \mathop = 1}^n U_i \in \mathcal F
}}
{{axiom | n = 4
        | m = \forall U \in \mathcal F: U \subseteq V \subseteq S \implies V \in \mathcal F
}}
{{end-axiom}}







Let $\mathcal F$ be a filter on $S$.


Then $S$ is said to be '''filtered by $\mathcal F$''', or just a '''filtered set'''.







A filter $\mathcal F$ on $S$ by definition specifically does ''not'' include the empty set $\O$.

If a filter $\mathcal F$ ''were'' to include $\O$, then from Empty Set is Subset of All Sets it would follow that ''every'' subset of $S$ would have to be in $\mathcal F$, and so $\mathcal F = \powerset S$.


Such a "filter" is called '''the trivial filter''' on $S$.

