10334:
A '''metric space''' $M = \struct {A, d}$ is an ordered pair consisting of:
: $(1): \quad$ a non-empty set $A$
together with:
: $(2): \quad$ a real-valued function $d: A \times A \to \R$ which acts on $A$, satisfying the metric space axioms:

{{begin-axiom}}
{{axiom | n = \text M 1
        | q = \forall x \in A
        | m = \map d {x, x} = 0
}}
{{axiom | n = \text M 2
        | q = \forall x, y, z \in A
        | m = \map d {x, y} + \map d {y, z} \ge \map d {x, z}
}}
{{axiom | n = \text M 3
        | q = \forall x, y \in A
        | m = \map d {x, y} = \map d {y, x}
}}
{{axiom | n = \text M 4
        | q = \forall x, y \in A
        | m = x \ne y \implies \map d {x, y} > 0
}}
{{end-axiom}}







The elements of $A$ are called the '''points''' of the space.







The mapping $d: A \times A \to \R$ is referred to as a '''distance function on $A$''' or simply '''distance'''.







Axiom $\text M 2$ is referred to as the '''triangle inequality''', as it is a generalization of the Triangle Inequality which holds on the real number line and complex plane.

10415:
Let $\left({S, \preccurlyeq}\right)$ be an ordered set.


A '''filter of $\left({S, \preccurlyeq}\right)$''' (or a '''filter on $\left({S, \preccurlyeq}\right)$''') is a subset $\mathcal F \subseteq S$ which satisfies the following conditions:

{{begin-axiom}}
{{axiom | n = 1
        | m = \mathcal F \ne \varnothing
}}
{{axiom | n = 2
        | m = x, y \in \mathcal F \implies \exists z \in \mathcal F: z \preccurlyeq x, z \preccurlyeq y
}}
{{axiom | n = 3
        | m = \forall x \in \mathcal F: \forall y \in S: x \preccurlyeq y \implies y \in \mathcal F
}}
{{end-axiom}}







Let $\mathcal F$ be a filter on $\left({S, \preccurlyeq}\right)$.


Then $\mathcal F$ is a '''proper filter''' on $S$ {{iff}} $\mathcal F \ne S$.

That is, {{iff}} $\mathcal F$ is a proper subset of $S$.

