11617:
A group is an algebraic structure $\struct {G, \circ}$ which satisfies the following four conditions:

{{begin-axiom}}
{{axiom | n = \text G 0
        | lc= Closure
        | q = \forall a, b \in G
        | m = a \circ b \in G
}}
{{axiom | n = \text G 1
        | lc= Associativity
        | q = \forall a, b, c \in G
        | m = a \circ \paren {b \circ c} = \paren {a \circ b} \circ c
}}
{{axiom | n = \text G 2
        | lc= Identity
        | q = \exists e \in G: \forall a \in G
        | m = e \circ a = a = a \circ e
}}
{{axiom | n = G 3
        | lc= Inverse
        | q = \forall a \in G: \exists b \in G
        | m = a \circ b = e = b \circ a
}}
{{end-axiom}}

These four stipulations are called the '''group axioms'''.

